MovieLens Data sets¶

Can we trust the ratings of movies to be unbiased?¶

Watching movies is one of the most popular pasttimes today. There are so many movies being released for streaming every year, and it is impossible to keep up with all of them. When someone is looking for a new movie to watch, he/she will often turn to movie-related sites, like IMDB or rotten tomatoes, which aggregate ratings, reviews, and other information about movies. One of the most important factors influencing one's decision to watch a movie is the overall rating. However, does the rating reasonably represent the entire population's opinion of the movie?

To address this question, I will use the enormous MovieLens data sets (http://movielens.org), which is collected by GroupLens Research (https://grouplens.org/datasets/movielens/). This dataset consists of more than 20 million ratings of nearly 30,000 movies, with around 130,000 users.

Let's start! First, let's import the python modules we need.

In [7]:
Movie['Title'] = Movie['title'].apply(lambda x:x.split(' (')[0])
Movie['Year'] = Movie['title'].apply(lambda x:re.findall(r"\([0-9]{4,7}\)", x))
Movie['Year'] = Movie['Year'].apply(lambda x:''.join(x))
Movie['genres']=Movie['genres'].apply(lambda x:re.sub("Sci-Fi", "SciFi", x))
Movie['genres']=Movie['genres'].apply(lambda x:re.sub("Film-Noir", "FilmNoir", x))

Now, I can look at the distribution of years that these movies were released.

The reason why the trend drops at the present is because this data doesn't include the end of the year. For more detailed analysis, let's try to distinguish movies by genre.

A given movie can have multiple genres. As the table above shows, the genres are separated by vertical lines. So, I want to one-hot encode the genre to make it easier to analyze movies as a function of their genre. I also want to get rid of 'IMAX' and '(no genres listed)'

The above table shows the combined datasets when I merge the movie table with the users and their ratings. Now, it is possible to track users behavior in their ratings. So, one way I could explore potential bias in a user's ratings is to assess whether a fan of a certain genre will rate movies of that genre higher/lower than the general public. First we need to define what is a fan of a genre.

Before going any further, I chose only the users who have rated at least one hundred movies (which represents the top 50,000 most active users).

In [13]:
MovieRating1 = MovieRating.copy()
temp = MovieRating1.groupby('userId').sum()[GenreListAll]
UserIdGenre1 = pd.DataFrame(temp.values/pd.DataFrame(temp.T.sum()).values,columns=GenreListAll,index=temp.index)
UserIdGenre1['TotalNumber']=MovieRating1.groupby('userId').count()['movieId']
CriteriaUserIdGenre1 = pd.DataFrame(UserIdGenre1.sort_values('TotalNumber',ascending=False).head(50000))

How can we define a group of fans for each genre?¶

Selecting the fans for each genre is a tough mission. In this project, I define fans for each genre as people who reviewed the specific genre more frequently compared to movies of other genres. For example, considering a person (person A) reviewed 1,000 movies in the dataset, and person A reviewed 300 SciFi movies out of the 1,000 they reviewed. I would consider person A to be a fan of SciFi (For the average person, SciFi movies only account for 6% of the movies they rated).

I will explain in detail in the charts below.

As seen in the chart above, the distribution is very different from the previous plots. In the case of these people, I will consider them to be fans of horror movies.

I selected fans of each genre following the steps below:

  1. Start by looking at the relative fraction of ratings by genre for the overall population. Then, it stands to reason that someone who is a fan of a certain genre, and who watches a disproportionately large fraction of movies in that genre, would rate movies in that genre more frequently than the average person does.

  2. Look for outliers who rated movies of that genre at a much higher frequency than the overall population.

The box-plot below shows the typical range of percentages of certain genres that users reviewed.

The colored boxes in the box-plot above highlight the 25%-75% range of the distribution for each genre that people reviewed. The upper whiskers corresponds to the top 1% of the distribution. Based on this information, I consider a fan to be a person who is identified as an outlier above the upper whiskers for each genre. For example, if someone has rated drama movies at more than 35%, I would define this person as a fan of drama (Look at the box graph for drama). Therefore, I chose 500 people (1% of total sample of 50,000) for each genre as the group of fans for that genre.

The script below derives the average ratings for each movie by fans of the genre and by non-fans. For the 18 genre categories, I chose the 30 movies which have the most total reviews and have at least 100 reviews from fans of the genre. The script below takes a long time to run (Here, I deleted the output cell in order to avoid confusion).

In [ ]:
CountMovieRating = MovieRating.groupby('title').sum()
for j in np.arange(len(GenreListAll)):
    temp = CountMovieRating.sort_values(GenreListAll[j],ascending=False)
    exec('Result'+str(GenreListAll[j])+'=DataFrame()')
    i=0; n=0
    while n<=30:
        name = temp.index[i]
        exec('G1 = pd.merge(Group1'+str(GenreListAll[j])+''',MovieRating[MovieRating['title']==name][['userId','rating']],on='userId',how='inner')''')
        if len(G1) >=100:
            exec('G2 = pd.merge(Group2'+str(GenreListAll[j])+''',MovieRating[MovieRating['title']==name][['userId','rating']],on='userId',how='inner')''') 
            print(i, n, GenreListAll[j],name,len(G1),round(G1['rating'].mean(),2),round(G1['rating'].std(),2),len(G2),round(G2['rating'].mean(),2),round(G2['rating'].std(),2))
            exec('Result'+str(GenreListAll[j])+'''[n]=[GenreListAll[j],name,len(G1),round(G1['rating'].mean(),2),round(G1['rating'].std(),2),len(G2),round(G2['rating'].mean(),2),round(G2['rating'].std(),2)]''')
            n+=1
        i+=1
        print(i)
        if i>100:
            break

def plotGenre(GenreName,Result1):
    CriteriaGenre=[GenreName]
    binsize=0.5
    for i in np.arange(len(CriteriaGenre)):
#        exec('Result1 = Result'+str(CriteriaGenre[i])+'.T')
        Result1.columns=[['Genre','title','NumFan','RatingFan','StdFan','NumPeo','RatingPeo','StdPeo']]
        Result1['Diff']=Result1['RatingFan']-Result1['RatingPeo']
        Result1 = Result1.set_index('title')

        temp = Result1[Result1['Genre']==CriteriaGenre[i]]
        x0 = np.arange(len(temp.sort_values('Diff',ascending=True)[temp.sort_values('Diff',ascending=True)['Diff']>=0]))
        x1 = np.arange(len(temp.sort_values('Diff',ascending=True)[temp.sort_values('Diff',ascending=True)['Diff']<0]))
        f = plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
        ax = f.add_axes([0.1, 0.1, 0.8, 0.8])
        ax.barh(x0+len(x1), temp.sort_values('Diff',ascending=True)[temp.sort_values('Diff',ascending=True)['Diff']>=0]['Diff'], binsize,color='orange')
        ax.barh(x1, temp.sort_values('Diff',ascending=True)[temp.sort_values('Diff',ascending=True)['Diff']<0]['Diff'], binsize,color='red')

        plt.title(CriteriaGenre[i],size=16)
        plt.xlabel('Rating(Fan) - Rating(General Public)',fontsize=14)
        ax.set_yticks(np.arange(len(temp))+0.3)
        ax.set_yticklabels(temp.sort_values('Diff',ascending=True).index,rotation=0)
        f.show()

The charts below show the difference between ratings from fans of the genre and non-fans. Overall, the ratings from the fans of the genre are systematically higher than those from non-fans. The orange bars extending to the right correspond to an increasingly positive bias by fans of that genre. The red bars extending to the left correspond to a negative bias by fans of that genre. The results below are sorted from largest positive bias to smallest.

For almost every genre, the most popular movies show a systematic positive bias in their reviews from fans of that genre. The one exception is Drama, which shows pretty even split between positive and negative bias, and indicates that perhaps the genre of drama is very vaguely defined and too commonplace. In other words, most people can be called a fan of drama, and therefore there is no net positive or negative bias in the reviews of drama movies.

Conclusion¶

To go back to my original question, is there bias in movie ratings? The answer is "Yes." As we can see above, the ratings of many movies will be affected by whether the person who is rating the movie is a fan of the movie's genre or not. The implication of this result is that you should be careful when checking the ratings of movies on IDMB or Rotten tomatoes, etc. A better indication of your potential interest in a movie can be determined by a more advanced movie recommendation engine, like what Netflix provides after you have rated many movies yourself, because the recommendation engine will take into account your own interests and biases.
